    <DocumentationNarrative Id="source:cli:meta-data-type-conversion:app:narrative:guide:working-with-type-conversion" DocumentationSubjectId="source:cli:meta-data-type-conversion:app" PreviousNarrativeId="source:cli:meta-data-type-conversion:app:narrative:summary:summary">
      <Body>MetaDataTypeConversion records the sanctioned paths between declared data types. A conversion states the source and target systems together with the length, precision, scale, fallback, and compatibility behavior that determine whether a value can move across a boundary.

The conversion workspace is shared policy. Transform binding uses it to evaluate source-to-target compatibility, and generators can apply the same approved behavior when they project a model into SQL or another platform. This avoids quietly embedding widening assumptions in individual tools.

Keeping conversion rules modeled also makes the hard cases visible. A design can be reviewed for loss, truncation, precision, and fallback choices before a transform or target is generated, and the resulting decision is reusable wherever the same type boundary appears.</Body>
      <BodyFormat>Markdown</BodyFormat>
